{
  "doc_id": "10159",
  "text": "Influential linguistic theories are based on the notion of an ideal speaker/hearer in a homogeneous speech community, and do not regard variation as interesting or informative [CITATION_1] . This view leads to the expectation that variation across the community is irrelevant for underlying representation (and for stating phonological alternations).",
